{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645245"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:14:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:14:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18099"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18099"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.1,0.05,0.86]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10813"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114534"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10813"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18099"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96535"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10579"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25172"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25438"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114534","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114534"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe vas deferens is a muscular tube that forms an essential part of the male reproductive tract.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of the vas deferens during ejaculation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Produces androgens for sperm maturation","Removes defective sperm cells","Functions as a sperm reservoir","Secretes nutrients for sperm cells","Transports sperm through muscular contractions"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etransport of sperm through muscular contractions\u003C/strong\u003E is the main function of the vas deferens. Its thick muscular wall contains smooth muscle that contracts rhythmically when stimulated by the autonomic nervous system, moving sperm from storage in the epididymis toward the urethra.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecreting nutrients for sperm cells\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by the accessory sex glands (seminal vesicles, prostate) which provide nutrients in seminal fluid. \u003Cstrong\u003EFunctioning as a sperm reservoir\u003C/strong\u003E is the role of the epididymis which serves as the primary site of sperm storage. \u003Cstrong\u003ERemoving defective sperm cells\u003C/strong\u003E is not a function of the vas deferens as it has no role in sperm selection or quality control. \u003Cstrong\u003EProducing androgens for sperm maturation\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in the testicular Leydig cells rather than the vas deferens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe vas deferens acts purely as a muscular conduit, using coordinated smooth muscle contractions to move sperm during ejaculation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The vas deferens contains thick smooth muscle that contracts rhythmically to transport sperm during ejaculation.","The vas deferens forms a muscular conduit between the epididymis and urethra.","Autonomic stimulation triggers contraction of the vas deferens smooth muscle during ejaculation."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 81; pg. 1017.","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96535"}},"question":{